## 3. Feature Specification
 
### 3.1 Text Extraction
 
| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Paste & Extract | User pastes Japanese text (email, chat, meeting notes) into a textarea. One-click or Cmd/Ctrl+Enter triggers extraction. |
| Auto-Chunking | Texts >1,500 chars are automatically split by sentence boundaries into ~500-char chunks. Chunk count displayed in UI hint. |
| Parallel Processing | Chunks are processed 3 at a time via Promise.allSettled. Partial failures don't block successful chunks. |
| Deduplication | Merged results are deduplicated by word (vocab), title (grammar), and original text (sentences). |
| JLPT Sorting | All extracted items are sorted by JLPT level: N5 → N4 → N3 → N2 → N1 → biz → other. Foundational words appear first. |
| Selection | All items are pre-selected by default. Known words are auto-deselected. Users can toggle individual items. |
 
### 3.2 Vocabulary Cards
 
#### Extracted Fields (Step 1)
 
- Word (kanji as-is from source text)
- Reading (full hiragana)
- Meaning (English, 2–5 words, work-context relevant)
- JLPT Level (N5, N4, N3, N2, N1, biz, other)
 
#### Enriched Fields (Step 2, On-Demand)
 
- 2–4 synonyms, each with: word, reading, meaning, JLPT level, nuance note (3–6 words)
- Example sentence from context with furigana on every kanji
- Nuance comparison tip (1 sentence comparing when to use each synonym)
- Synonyms that are in the user's Known Words list are tagged "known"
 
#### Card Display Behavior
 
- Known words are visually dimmed (opacity 0.7) with "known" tag
- Click card body to toggle selection
- Click "Load synonyms" to trigger enrichment API call
- Click "Hide synonyms" to collapse enriched content
- Error state shown inline if enrichment fails
 
### 3.3 Grammar Cards
 
#### Extracted Fields
 
- Title (grammar pattern, e.g. ～に伴い)
- Explanation (when/how to use, 1 sentence)
- Example sentence with furigana
- JLPT Level (all levels including non-JLPT/business patterns)
 
#### Coverage Rules
 
- Extracts ALL grammar patterns at every level (N5 through N1)
- Includes business-specific patterns (keigo, email conventions)
- Includes non-JLPT colloquial patterns
- Basic particles (は, が, の, で, に, を, です, ます) are skipped unless they form part of a grammar pattern
 
### 3.4 Sentence Cards
 
Sentence cards train the user to parse real Japanese text in context — the skill gap between knowing isolated vocabulary and reading actual workplace emails.
 
#### Auto-Suggested Sentences
 
- During extraction, the LLM picks 3–5 most useful/representative full sentences from the source text
- Sentences are automatically selected for inclusion in the deck
 
#### Manual Sentence Addition
 
- Input field below the sentence section allows pasting custom sentences
- Added sentences appear immediately in the extraction results
- Custom sentences can also be enriched on-demand
 
#### Enriched Fields (On-Demand)
 
- **Furigana:** Full sentence rewritten with furigana in parentheses after every kanji compound
- **English:** Natural translation (not word-by-word)
- **Key Vocab:** 3–6 most important/difficult words highlighted as chips with reading and meaning
 
#### Anki Card Format
 
- Front: Original kanji sentence (challenges the user to read it)
- Back: Furigana version + English translation + key vocab highlighted
- Tagged as "sentence" in TSV export
 
### 3.5 Known Words System
 
The Known Words system prevents redundant card creation by tracking vocabulary the user has already learned.
 
#### Import from Anki
 
- User exports existing Anki cards (Browse → select → Export Notes)
- Paste the export text into the Known Words import textarea
- Flexible parser handles: one word per line, TSV, CSV, numbered lists, Anki export format
- Auto-strips readings in parentheses, numbering prefixes, emoji/bullet prefixes
- Live preview shows "~47 words detected" before import
 
#### Auto-Tracking
 
- Every vocabulary word added to the Deck via "Add to Deck" is automatically added to the Known Words set
- No manual action required — the system learns what you've studied over time
 
#### Extraction Behavior
 
- Known words are auto-deselected (not checked by default)
- Known words are visually dimmed with an "already known" tag
- Summary bar shows: "12 new · 5 already known"
- Toggle checkbox: "Hide known" to show only new vocabulary
- Synonyms within enrichment that match known words show a "known" badge
 
#### Known Words Management
 
- Dedicated "Known" tab showing all tracked words as chips
- Alphabetically sorted display
- Individual removal (click × on any chip)
- Bulk clear option
- Persistent storage across sessions
 
### 3.6 Deck Management
 
| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Add to Deck | Adds all selected vocab, grammar, and sentence cards. Enrichment data (synonyms, nuance tips, furigana) is baked into cards if loaded. |
| Deduplication | Cards already in the deck (matched by word/title/sentence) are skipped with count shown. |
| Deck Stats | Header shows: N vocab · N grammar · N sentences. |
| Card Removal | Individual card removal via × button. |
| Clear All | Removes all cards from deck with confirmation toast. |
| Persistent Storage | Deck and Known Words saved via window.storage API, persists across sessions. |
 
### 3.7 Anki Export
 
#### TSV Format
 
Export generates a tab-separated values file compatible with Anki's import function:
 
- Column 1 (Front): Word with reading / grammar pattern / original sentence
- Column 2 (Back): Meaning, example, synonyms, nuance tip, furigana, English translation, key vocab — all included
- Column 3 (Tags): "vocab", "grammar", or "sentence"
 
#### Export Method
 
- Primary: Clipboard copy (navigator.clipboard.writeText)
- Fallback: Modal with textarea for manual select-all + copy
 
#### Import Instructions
 
Anki: File → Import → select .tsv file → set separator to Tab → map 3 columns: Front / Back / Tags.
 
